caseText:"<p>Hydrogen fuel cells represent a cutting-edge technological development that is widely expected to replace conveal petrol and diesel engines in heavy motor vehicles such as buses and trucks. With the urgent need to reduce carbon emissions, green energy initiatives have become a global priority and are being actively promoted by governments through various policy measures and incentive programs. For this technology to become commercially viable, a comprehensive supporting ecosystem must be developed, including service centers, hydrogen fuel storage and distribution infrastructure, and other essential facilities.</p> <p>H-Power is a large petroleum oil refining company that has diversified into the manufacturing of green hydrogen fuel cells over the past five years. Green hydrogen is considered significantly more environmentally friendly than grey hydrogen, as the latter is produced using fossil fuels such as natural gas or coal. In contrast, green hydrogen is generated using renewable energy sources such as solar and wind power, enabling a substantial reduction in carbon emissions.</p> <p>Hydrogen, as a standalone gas, is scarce in nature; however, it is abundantly available as a component of water, which consists of hydrogen and oxygen. The production of green hydrogen relies on electrolysis, a process in which an electrolyzer splits water into hydrogen and oxygen using renewable electricity. Electrolysers are therefore a critical input in the green hydrogen value chain. Ecopower is a manufacturer of hydrogen electrolysers and has been a key supplier to H-Power for its hydrogen fuel operations. Recently, H-Power has been in discussions to acquire Ecopower for a consideration of USD 1 billion. This acquisition would significantly strengthen H-Power&rsquo;s production capabilities, although building and scaling such capabilities is highly capital intensive and requires investments running into billions of dollars.</p> <p>The adoption of hydrogen fuel technology is heavily influenced by the cost of hydrogen production. At present, the cost of producing grey hydrogen is substantially lower than that of green hydrogen. As a result, grey hydrogen continues to be more widely adopted by both fuel producers and manufacturers of buses and trucks. In response, H-Power has begun collaborating closely with&nbsp;bus and truck manufacturers to increase awareness and understanding of green hydrogen technology. It has successfully persuaded a few large manufacturers to modify engine designs on an experimental basis to accommodate green hydrogen fuel.</p> <p>As noted earlier, the long-term viability of this business is dependent not only on the technology itself but also on the development of a complete supporting ecosystem, including service infrastructure, fuel storage, and distribution networks. While government support in the form of policy initiatives and subsidies has provided momentum to this transition, the complexity of shifting to green energy means that H-Power must remain prepared to face potential roadblocks arising from policy changes, regulatory uncertainty, and implementation delays.</p> <p>Given that this represents a new line of business for the company, H-Power seeks to identify and understand the key building blocks required to deliver value to its customers. To achieve this, the company is using Osterwalder&rsquo;s Business Model Canvas as a framework for analysis.</p>",    
questions:[{question:"On the Business Canvas Model, H-Power’s decision to acquire Ecopower would represent a shift from:",
    options:["Key Resources segment to Key Partners segment ",
        "Key Activities segment to Cost segment",
        "Key Partners segment to Key Resources segment ",
        "Key Resources segment to Channels "],answer:2},
{question:"If the eco-system of service and distribution centers is unable to be developed, which link on the Business Canvas Model of H-Power would most likely break?",
    options:["Link between value proposition and customer segment. ",
        "Link between key activities and value proposition",
        "Link between key resources and key partners ",
        "Link between cost structure and revenue streams"],answer:0},
{question:"Using the Triple Bottom Line framework, H-power’s collaboration with bus and truck manufacturers to modify their engines represents:",
    options:["A purely environmental initiative (Plant) ",
        "A purely financial initiative (Profit)",
        "An integrated approach that will have a positive environmental impact (Planet) as well as ensures market viability (Profit)",
        "Has no impact on any of the three pillars of the TBL framework "],answer:2},
{question:"In order to develop a sustainable business in the long term, on which of the following should H-Power be less dependent on?",
    options:["ensuring availability of critical resources like water, electrolyzers, skilled manpower etc",
        "reduction in the cost of production of green hydrogen fuel ",
        "early and wide-spread adoption of green hydrogen fuel technology among automobile manufacturers and end users ",
        "government policy initiatives and subsidies to make it a viable business"],answer:3},
{question:"While understanding the business canvas, given the capital-intensive nature of key resources (assets that are used to build production capabilities), what strategy should H-Power adopt to manage its revenue stream:  ",
    options:["Relying on spot-market prices of green hydrogen to capitalize on short-term market fluctuations ",
        "Securing long-term contracts with automobile manufacturers and leveraging government support when available",
        "Focus on selling electrolyzers to recoup the investment made in this technology ",
        "Right from the beginning, compete with the price of grey hydrogen fuel in order to penetrate and grow market share "],answer:1}
    ]
